"I think, therefore, I am."

3
00:00:07,273 --> 00:00:08,807
But am I?

4
00:00:08,808 --> 00:00:10,475
I think. Ha.

5
00:00:10,476 --> 00:00:14,279
A single microscopic brain cell
cannot think,

6
00:00:14,280 --> 00:00:15,247
is not conscious,

7
00:00:15,248 --> 00:00:17,515
but if you bring in
a few more brain cells,

8
00:00:17,516 --> 00:00:18,583
and a few more,
and connect them all,

9
00:00:18,584 --> 00:00:21,820
at a certain point,
the group itself will 

10
00:00:21,821 --> 00:00:24,089
be able to think

11
00:00:24,090 --> 00:00:25,824
and experience emotions

12
00:00:25,825 --> 00:00:27,826
and have opinions
and a personality

13
00:00:27,827 --> 00:00:30,662
and know that it exists.

14
00:00:30,663 --> 00:00:32,429
How can such astonishing things

15
00:00:32,430 --> 00:00:35,300
be made from
such simple ingredients?

16
00:00:35,301 --> 00:00:38,503
Well, answering that question
means learning not only who
we are,

17
00:00:38,504 --> 00:00:42,373
but, more importantly,
 how we are.

18
00:00:42,374 --> 00:00:46,311
Today, using what
neuroscientists know so far,

19
00:00:46,312 --> 00:00:48,746
I am going to make my hometown

20
00:00:48,747 --> 00:00:51,649
function like a brain!

21
00:00:51,650 --> 00:00:57,622
( all cheering, applauding )

22
00:00:57,623 --> 00:01:11,736
 ♪

23
00:01:11,737 --> 00:01:14,772
A single brain cell is tiny,

24
00:01:14,773 --> 00:01:18,343
both in size and abilities.

25
00:01:18,344 --> 00:01:22,180
But when enough are together,
they can do amazing things

26
00:01:22,181 --> 00:01:25,350
like be aware of themselves.

27
00:01:25,351 --> 00:01:28,720
When the collective power
of a group working together

28
00:01:28,721 --> 00:01:31,489
is greater than the sum
of their individual parts,

29
00:01:31,490 --> 00:01:33,892
that is called "emergence."

30
00:01:33,893 --> 00:01:36,427
In a similar fashion,
we as individuals

31
00:01:36,428 --> 00:01:38,429
are connected to
the people around us.

32
00:01:38,430 --> 00:01:41,766
Those connections
form communities that,
when functioning properly,

33
00:01:41,767 --> 00:01:44,936
can work together
to accomplish amazing feats.

34
00:01:44,937 --> 00:01:48,606
A great example is
"wisdom of the crowds."

35
00:01:48,607 --> 00:01:51,609
Even if not a single person
in a crowd

36
00:01:51,610 --> 00:01:54,179
knows the right answer
to a question,

37
00:01:54,180 --> 00:01:58,449
collectively, they could all
somehow know the right answer.

38
00:01:58,450 --> 00:02:01,186
In 1987, economist
Jack Treynor

39
00:02:01,187 --> 00:02:03,955
conducted
the "Bean Jar" experiment.

40
00:02:03,956 --> 00:02:09,260
He asked 56 students
to guess the number
of jellybeans in a jar.

41
00:02:09,261 --> 00:02:11,496
Now, as you can probably guess,

42
00:02:11,497 --> 00:02:14,232
not a single one of them
guessed the right answer.

43
00:02:14,233 --> 00:02:18,469
But amazingly, when he took
the average of their guesses,

44
00:02:18,470 --> 00:02:22,607
what he got was a number within
just 3% of the real answer.

45
00:02:22,608 --> 00:02:25,276
Now, some people
guessed way too high,

46
00:02:25,277 --> 00:02:27,579
but others guessed
way too low,

47
00:02:27,580 --> 00:02:30,648
so all together,
their errors balanced out,

48
00:02:30,649 --> 00:02:33,351
and from a whole bunch
of wrong guesses,

49
00:02:33,352 --> 00:02:36,354
the true answer emerged.

50
00:02:36,355 --> 00:02:37,755
What else can a crowd do?

51
00:02:37,756 --> 00:02:39,490
If I got a bunch
of humans together

52
00:02:39,491 --> 00:02:42,727
and had each one of them
act like a brain cell,

53
00:02:42,728 --> 00:02:46,231
turning on or off in response
to the actions of other people,

54
00:02:46,232 --> 00:02:48,566
could I make a neural network

55
00:02:48,567 --> 00:02:51,336
like the one in our brain?

56
00:02:51,337 --> 00:02:53,538
And if I had enough people,

57
00:02:53,539 --> 00:02:56,908
could intelligence, emotions,

58
00:02:56,909 --> 00:02:58,977
a mind, emerge?

59
00:02:58,978 --> 00:03:01,546
 If I recruited
 every single person

60
00:03:01,547 --> 00:03:03,581
 in the country of China

61
00:03:03,582 --> 00:03:05,817
 and arranged them like neurons,

62
00:03:05,818 --> 00:03:08,620
 would the result not only be
 a simple brain,

63
00:03:08,621 --> 00:03:11,623
 but something that can think
 and feel

64
00:03:11,624 --> 00:03:13,858
 and be aware of
 its own existence?

65
00:03:13,859 --> 00:03:16,861
Well, this is the China Brain
thought experiment,

66
00:03:16,862 --> 00:03:20,665
first proposed by Lawrence Davis
and, later, Ned Block.

67
00:03:20,666 --> 00:03:24,936
It's never been done before
and, well, unfortunately,

68
00:03:24,937 --> 00:03:27,272
I don't have access
to everyone in China.

69
00:03:27,273 --> 00:03:29,407
I made some calls,
and like a lot of them are busy.

70
00:03:29,408 --> 00:03:32,644
But the first step is to see
what a crowd in real life

71
00:03:32,645 --> 00:03:33,645
could even do.

72
00:03:33,646 --> 00:03:35,546
This hasn't been done
successfully before,

73
00:03:35,547 --> 00:03:38,650
but I want to blow
a neural network

74
00:03:38,651 --> 00:03:40,551
up to the scale of a crowd.

75
00:03:40,552 --> 00:03:43,755
And what better crowd to use
than one made of the people

76
00:03:43,756 --> 00:03:47,458
whose emergent properties
made me who I am today?

77
00:03:47,459 --> 00:03:50,728
That's right, I am going home
to Stilwell, Kansas.

