I wrote a book called
 How to Build a Brain.

115
00:05:33,832 --> 00:05:35,967
Michael:
 Chris is known for
 is neural network,

116
00:05:35,968 --> 00:05:38,703
 the Semantic Pointer
 Architecture Unified Network,

117
00:05:38,704 --> 00:05:41,506
 or SPAUN, which is one of
 the world's most complex

118
00:05:41,507 --> 00:05:43,941
 computer simulations
 of the brain.

119
00:05:43,942 --> 00:05:46,744
 It uses 6.6 million
 simulated neurons

120
00:05:46,745 --> 00:05:49,580
 to perform functions
 like counting, reasoning,

121
00:05:49,581 --> 00:05:51,416
 and image recognition.

122
00:05:51,417 --> 00:05:52,850
 SPAUN is cutting-edge,

123
00:05:52,851 --> 00:05:54,952
 but neural networks
 are nothing new.

124
00:05:54,953 --> 00:05:57,422
 The first was made
 by Dr. Frank Rosenblatt

125
00:05:57,423 --> 00:06:00,525
 of Cornell University in 1957.

126
00:06:00,526 --> 00:06:02,860
 His network, called
 the Perceptron,

127
00:06:02,861 --> 00:06:04,929
 was designed for
 image recognition,

128
00:06:04,930 --> 00:06:07,532
 and he hoped it would become
 capable of learning,

129
00:06:07,533 --> 00:06:08,767
 just like a brain.

130
00:06:08,768 --> 00:06:10,902
 But the project was only
 partially successful,

131
00:06:10,903 --> 00:06:14,038
 and after some controversy,
 fell by the wayside.

132
00:06:14,039 --> 00:06:16,808
 It was only when researchers
 in the 1980s

133
00:06:16,809 --> 00:06:18,776
 came back upon
 Dr. Rosenblatt's work,

134
00:06:18,777 --> 00:06:20,745
 and as computing power
 increased,

135
00:06:20,746 --> 00:06:22,914
 that the field of artificial
 neural networks

136
00:06:22,915 --> 00:06:24,682
 came back to the mainstream.

137
00:06:24,683 --> 00:06:26,784
 Today, it is alive and well.

138
00:06:26,785 --> 00:06:30,221
 SPAUN, and even neural networks
 used in self-driving cars,

139
00:06:30,222 --> 00:06:35,660
 are expanding the possibilities
 of computer learning.

140
00:06:35,661 --> 00:06:38,496
If I want to make
a brain out of people,
where do I start?

141
00:06:38,497 --> 00:06:39,597
That's a good question.

142
00:06:39,598 --> 00:06:41,532
I think the first thing
we want to do is figure out

143
00:06:41,533 --> 00:06:42,900
what we want our brain to do.

144
00:06:42,901 --> 00:06:44,769
I would recommend
something like vision.

145
00:06:44,770 --> 00:06:49,607
Vision. Let's make
this brain see.

146
00:06:49,608 --> 00:06:51,542
Michael:
 Before we can design
 the intricacies

147
00:06:51,543 --> 00:06:52,743
 of the brain we're making,

148
00:06:52,744 --> 00:06:55,513
 let's look at how
 visual processing works.

149
00:06:55,514 --> 00:06:58,082
 Let's say we look at a cat.

150
00:06:58,083 --> 00:07:00,618
 Light information
 from every point on the cat

151
00:07:00,619 --> 00:07:02,220
 lands on the retina.

152
00:07:02,221 --> 00:07:05,990
 This information gets sent
 to our visual cortex.

153
00:07:05,991 --> 00:07:08,693
 The visual cortex 
 is structured in layers--

154
00:07:08,694 --> 00:07:10,828
 V1 through V6.

155
00:07:10,829 --> 00:07:12,930
 Each of these layers
 are made up of neurons

156
00:07:12,931 --> 00:07:14,799
 activated by specific features,

157
00:07:14,800 --> 00:07:17,835
 like lines, angles, and shapes.

158
00:07:17,836 --> 00:07:19,237
 The features that are detected

159
00:07:19,238 --> 00:07:21,639
 are sent to
 the infratemporal cortex

160
00:07:21,640 --> 00:07:23,808
 which puts all the pieces
 of the image together,

161
00:07:23,809 --> 00:07:25,977
 and we get our Eureka! moment

162
00:07:25,978 --> 00:07:28,079
 where we recognize
 the object we're looking at,

163
00:07:28,080 --> 00:07:32,016
 what it means what feelings
 we have towards it.

164
00:07:32,017 --> 00:07:33,784
I love cats.

165
00:07:33,785 --> 00:07:36,754
But what should we have
our brain recognize?

166
00:07:36,755 --> 00:07:38,289
We don't want
really high resolution images

167
00:07:38,290 --> 00:07:40,258
or images that depend
on too much detail,

168
00:07:40,259 --> 00:07:42,193
- Ok.
- so things like letters
and digits.

169
00:07:42,194 --> 00:07:43,294
Let's say we use digits. Ok?

170
00:07:43,295 --> 00:07:46,631
- Ok.
- I want to be the one
who draws a digit,

171
00:07:46,632 --> 00:07:50,034
and then you will be
on the output side.

172
00:07:50,035 --> 00:07:53,905
You should be able
to determine what I've drawn;

173
00:07:53,906 --> 00:07:56,874
not because I showed it
to someone and they
telephoned it back to you,

174
00:07:56,875 --> 00:08:00,111
but because
they processed it
intelligently.

175
00:08:00,112 --> 00:08:01,712
That's what we need
to figure out,

176
00:08:01,713 --> 00:08:03,648
how we're gonna
show an input to our people.

177
00:08:03,649 --> 00:08:05,182
So we should take
some small number of them

178
00:08:05,183 --> 00:08:07,318
and put them at the front,
as the retina,

179
00:08:07,319 --> 00:08:09,087
and really just show them each
a little bit of the image.

180
00:08:09,088 --> 00:08:13,925
So if, for instance,
we're able to put like
25 people in that kind
of front row,

181
00:08:13,926 --> 00:08:17,028
the "input" layer,
then whatever image we show

182
00:08:17,029 --> 00:08:19,797
should be made up
of 25 pixels.

183
00:08:19,798 --> 00:08:21,132
- Exactly. Right.
- Twenty-five pieces.

184
00:08:21,133 --> 00:08:23,868
I'm gonna draw
25 people.

185
00:08:23,869 --> 00:08:25,736
1, 2, 3, 4, 5,

186
00:08:25,737 --> 00:08:27,805
6, 7, 8, 9, 10,

187
00:08:27,806 --> 00:08:29,707
11, 12, 13, 14, 15,

188
00:08:29,708 --> 00:08:31,909
16, 17, 18, 19, 20,

189
00:08:31,910 --> 00:08:34,678
21, 22, 23, 24, 25.

190
00:08:34,679 --> 00:08:35,812
See? I can count.

191
00:08:35,813 --> 00:08:38,316
These are our retina cells,

192
00:08:38,317 --> 00:08:40,117
and each one is
an individual person

193
00:08:40,118 --> 00:08:42,753
that's literally standing,
like, in a field.

194
00:08:42,754 --> 00:08:44,187
What do they then do next?

195
00:08:44,188 --> 00:08:46,090
They merely need to indicate
whether or not

196
00:08:46,091 --> 00:08:47,758
their cell is on or off.

197
00:08:47,759 --> 00:08:49,927
- All right.
- So, they should start firing.

198
00:08:49,928 --> 00:08:51,162
They should start spiking
like a neuron.

199
00:08:51,163 --> 00:08:52,964
What could they do
to indicate

200
00:08:52,965 --> 00:08:54,932
that they're firing or not?

201
00:08:54,933 --> 00:08:56,834
They could jump up and down,

202
00:08:56,835 --> 00:08:58,636
they could wave a flag...

203
00:08:58,637 --> 00:09:00,204
OK, I like that.

204
00:09:00,205 --> 00:09:03,240
When Chris and I use words
like "firing" and "spiking,"

205
00:09:03,241 --> 00:09:05,676
we're talking about
how brain cells, neurons,

206
00:09:05,677 --> 00:09:06,944
talk to one another

207
00:09:06,945 --> 00:09:11,716
by sending an electric message
from one cell...

208
00:09:11,717 --> 00:09:12,584
to another.

209
00:09:12,585 --> 00:09:14,652
It's called
an "action potential,"

210
00:09:14,653 --> 00:09:17,154
and it travels down the axon
of the cell.

211
00:09:17,155 --> 00:09:19,724
When the ionic flow
into a brain cell

212
00:09:19,725 --> 00:09:20,859
reaches a certain threshold,

213
00:09:20,860 --> 00:09:24,362
the cell will fire an electronic
message down its axon.

214
00:09:24,363 --> 00:09:27,164
So a neuron
can either be on or off.

215
00:09:27,165 --> 00:09:29,767
It's either firing
or it's not firing.

216
00:09:29,768 --> 00:09:32,269
What we need to find
is a way for a person

217
00:09:32,270 --> 00:09:34,038
to be either on or off--

218
00:09:34,039 --> 00:09:37,341
raising a flag or their hand
should do the trick.

219
00:09:37,342 --> 00:09:39,276
 To illustrate our visual input,

220
00:09:39,277 --> 00:09:41,679
 I will be drawing a number
 from 0 to 9

221
00:09:41,680 --> 00:09:45,249
 onto a grid divided
 into 25 squares, or pixels.

222
00:09:45,250 --> 00:09:48,953
 Now each person, or neuron,
 will receive one pixel.

223
00:09:48,954 --> 00:09:51,122
 If a neuron receives
 a pixel with writing on it,

224
00:09:51,123 --> 00:09:52,923
 it will fire.

225
00:09:52,924 --> 00:09:55,893
 The V1 layer identifies
 pixels in the retinal layer

226
00:09:55,894 --> 00:09:58,362
 that form particular lines
 in the number,

227
00:09:58,363 --> 00:10:01,732
 and the V2 layer identifies
 particular combinations

228
00:10:01,733 --> 00:10:05,002
 of lines from V1
 that form angles.

229
00:10:05,003 --> 00:10:08,739
- What does V3 do?
- V3 is more sensitive to color.

230
00:10:08,740 --> 00:10:10,141
We're only working with
black and white in this case.

231
00:10:10,142 --> 00:10:12,343
So you're saying we won't even
need to have a V3 in our brain?

232
00:10:12,344 --> 00:10:13,911
We're skipping V3 altogether.

233
00:10:13,912 --> 00:10:15,746
All right, sorry, V3.

234
00:10:15,747 --> 00:10:18,215
- So we're gonna go
 straight to V4?
- Yeah.

235
00:10:18,216 --> 00:10:19,850
Michael:
 V4 neurons will fire

236
00:10:19,851 --> 00:10:22,019
 when their assigned
 combinations of angles

237
00:10:22,020 --> 00:10:23,187
 have been detected.

238
00:10:23,188 --> 00:10:25,156
 At this point
 the basic shape of a number

239
00:10:25,157 --> 00:10:26,924
 is beginning to take form.

240
00:10:26,925 --> 00:10:29,894
And so actually the next one
is called IT.

241
00:10:29,895 --> 00:10:32,363
- Ooh!
- And that stands for
 infratemporal cortex.

242
00:10:32,364 --> 00:10:33,931
Michael:
 Now don't worry.

243
00:10:33,932 --> 00:10:35,900
 We haven't forgotten V5 and V6.

244
00:10:35,901 --> 00:10:37,768
 They exist, they're responsible

245
00:10:37,769 --> 00:10:40,271
 for higher-level image
 processing in our brain.

246
00:10:40,272 --> 00:10:43,340
 But for our demonstration,
 we don't need them.

247
00:10:43,341 --> 00:10:46,377
 We do, however, need
 the infratemporal cortex,

248
00:10:46,378 --> 00:10:48,979
 which is the final layer needed
 for visual processing

249
00:10:48,980 --> 00:10:50,748
 in the brain we're designing.

250
00:10:50,749 --> 00:10:52,950
 Our IT will consist
